{
  "texts": [
    "In this study, we examine whether genotypes from wild populations of the tree crop Theobroma cacao L. (diverged 40 k-900 k generations) can be used to efficiently identify genes conferring resistance to the oomycete pathogen Phytophthora palmivora [9].",
    "Like all plants with long generation times (~5 years in T. cacao), this cannot be accomplished by breeding and back-crossing for mapping genes of interest, suggesting our methods may be foundational for future studies of other slow-tomature plant species.Theobroma cacao L., the seeds of which are the raw material for chocolate, is a tropical understory plant native to the Amazon basin [10][11][12].",
    "Cocoa and cocoa butter, the products created by fermenting, drying, and processing cacao seeds (\"beans\"), form the basis of a chocolate and confectionary market worth approximately $100 billion [11,13].",
    "Cacao genotypes are distributed across at least thirteen strongly differentiated population groups that are hypothesized to have evolved in partial isolation created by ancient ridgelines, glacial refugia, and/or human management [11,[14][15][16][17].",
    "Divergence times among populations are hypothesized to be between 40,000 and 900,000 generations [9]."
  ]
}